#names(DF)

###Renaming variables

names(DF)[names(DF) == "riagendr"] <- "sex" ##Gender
names(DF)[names(DF) == "ridageyr"] <- "age"##Age of respondent
names(DF)[names(DF) == "indfmin2"] <- "Income"
names(DF)[names(DF) == "ridreth3"] <- "Ethincity" ##Ethinicity
names(DF)[names(DF) == "dmdmartl"] <- "Marital"##marital status1,2,3,4,5 (ever married) vs 5(never married)
names(DF)[names(DF) == "dmdeduc2"] <- "Edu" ##Education <=2 >2

##Replacing missing values by 99

DF[is.na(DF)] <- 99

##Recoding Variables

DF$Edu_c<-ifelse(DF$Edu<=3,0,ifelse(DF$Edu>3&DF$Edu<99,1,99))
DF$Income_c<-ifelse(DF$Income<=8,0,ifelse(DF$Income>8&DF$Income<77,1,99))

##Replacing Specific Value by other values( Example: merging two categories in Ethnicity)

DF$Ethincity[DF$Ethincity == "7"] <-"6"

##Why survey weighting is important ##see https://survalyzer.com/weighting-survey-data/ ##Descriptive statistics with continuous variables ##calculating the mean of a continuous variable.

###For more than one variables

svymean(~age+Income, SDes, na=TRUE)
##          mean     SE
## age    37.238 0.2222
## Income 24.422 0.6650
svysd(~age+Income, SDes)
##        std. dev.
## age       22.396
## Income    33.588

##Mean with 95% CI For more than one variables

confint(svymean(~age+Income, SDes))
##           2.5 %   97.5 %
## age    36.80229 37.67323
## Income 23.11865 25.72536
cbind(svymean(~age+Income, SDes, na=TRUE), confint(svymean(~age+Income, SDes)))
##                    2.5 %   97.5 %
## age    37.23776 36.80229 37.67323
## Income 24.42201 23.11865 25.72536

####The coefficient of variation. ##The coefficient of variation is the ratio of the standard error to the mean, multiplied by 100%. ##It is an indication of the variability relative to the mean in the population ##It is not affected by the unit of measurement of the variable.

cv(svymean(~age+Income,design = SDes, na = TRUE))
##         age      Income 
## 0.005966634 0.027229097

ROC Analysis

##Assess test performance: Measures ability to distinguish disease vs.non-disease. ##AUC provides a single performance metric. ##Compare models: Identifies the best diagnostic or predictive model. ##Select thresholds: Balances sensitivity and specificity for clinical needs. ##Visualize results: Graphically represents model performance. ##Guide decisions: Supports better diagnostic and treatment strategies. ##Highlight trade-offs: Shows sensitivity vs.specificity balance. ##Handle imbalances: Works well with uneven disease prevalence.

library(pROC)
## Type 'citation("pROC")' for a citation.
## 
## Attaching package: 'pROC'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     cov, smooth, var
library(ROCR)

Calculate ROC curve for unweighted data

fit= glm(chronic_binary~ Income_c+age+sex, data=DF, family=binomial(link="logit"))
# Create prediction object
pred <- prediction(fit$fitted.values, chronic_binary)
# Calculate performance (True Positive Rate and False Positive Rate)
perf <- performance(pred, "tpr", "fpr")

# Plot the ROC curve
plot(perf, col = "darkgreen", lwd = 2, main = "ROC Curve with ROCR")

# Add a diagonal reference line
abline(a = 0, b = 1, col = "red", lty = 2)
